body:
# DuckDB Files

DuckDB makes files look like tables. This is the core workflow for local analysis, research datasets, CI data checks, and one-off conversions.

## Direct Reads

```sql
-- Shorthand works for common formats
SELECT * FROM 'events.parquet' LIMIT 10;
SELECT * FROM 'users.csv' LIMIT 10;

-- Explicit readers expose options
SELECT * FROM read_csv('users.csv', header = true, union_by_name = true);
SELECT * FROM read_parquet('events/*.parquet');
SELECT * FROM read_json_auto('logs.ndjson');
```

## Multiple Files and Globs

```sql
-- All Parquet files under a tree
SELECT count(*) FROM read_parquet('warehouse/events/**/*.parquet');

-- Multiple folders
SELECT * FROM read_parquet(['a/*.parquet', 'b/*.parquet']);

-- CSV files with schema drift
SELECT *
FROM read_csv(['jan.csv', 'feb.csv'], union_by_name = true, filename = true);
```

Use `union_by_name = true` when files may have columns in different orders or a subset of columns. Add `filename = true` when provenance matters.

## Partitioned Data

```sql
SELECT region, count()
FROM read_parquet('s3://bucket/events/year=*/month=*/*.parquet', hive_partitioning = true)
WHERE year = 2026 AND month = 4
GROUP BY ALL
ORDER BY ALL;
```

Hive-style partition paths such as `year=2026/month=04/file.parquet` can become columns. Filter on partition columns early for cheaper scans.

## COPY Import and Export

```sql
-- Persist a file scan into a DuckDB table
CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE events AS
SELECT * FROM read_parquet('events/*.parquet');

-- Export a query to Parquet
COPY (
  SELECT status, count() AS n
  FROM events
  GROUP BY status
  ORDER BY status
) TO 'status_counts.parquet' (FORMAT parquet);

-- Export CSV with header
COPY events TO 'events.csv' (HEADER, DELIMITER ',');
```

## Format Conversion

```sql
-- CSV to Parquet
COPY (
  SELECT * FROM read_csv('raw.csv', union_by_name = true)
) TO 'clean.parquet' (FORMAT parquet, COMPRESSION zstd);

-- JSON Lines to Parquet
COPY (
  SELECT * FROM read_json_auto('logs.ndjson')
) TO 'logs.parquet' (FORMAT parquet);
```

## Remote Files

HTTPS and S3-compatible reads use [[duckdb/extensions#httpfs]] and [[duckdb/secrets]]. Core extensions can autoload, but explicit setup is clearer in scripts.

```sql
INSTALL httpfs;
LOAD httpfs;

SELECT count()
FROM read_parquet('https://example.com/data/events.parquet');
```
